First of all, I run the program and see how it behaves:

```bash
./level7 
Segmentation fault (core dumped)
./level7 AAAA
Segmentation fault (core dumped)
./level7 AAAA BBBB
~~
```

Nothing special happens. The program prints a "~~" message and exits.

At this point I know two things:

* the program expects two arguments (properly).
* user controlled data is probably processed somewhere.

To understand what happens internally, I decide to inspect the assembly code:

```bash
echo 'disassemble main' | gdb -q ./level7
```

The first thing that catches my attention is the repeated calls to `malloc`:

```asm
movl   $0x8,(%esp)
call   malloc
```

This appears four times.

Since every allocation size is `8`, I start following how the returned pointers are used.

After the first allocation:

```asm
call malloc
mov %eax,0x1c(%esp)
```

the returned heap pointer is stored on the stack.

A few instructions later:

```asm
mov 0x1c(%esp),%eax
movl $0x1,(%eax)
```

The value `1` is written at offset `0`.

Then:

```asm
mov %edx,0x4(%eax)
```

Something that looks like a pointer is written at offset `4`.

At this point I can reconstruct the layout:

```text
offset 0 -> integer
offset 4 -> pointer
```

which looks like:

```c
struct S
{
    int n;
    char *buf;
};
```

The size is:

```text
int     = 4 bytes
pointer = 4 bytes
-----------------
total   = 8 bytes
```

which perfectly matches the `malloc(8)`.

A little later I see exactly the same pattern again:

```asm
mov     $0x8,(%esp)
call    0x80483f0 <malloc@plt>
mov     %eax,0x18(%esp)
mov     0x18(%esp),%eax
movl    $0x2,(%eax)
```

so there are actually two structures:

```c
s1
s2
```

each one containing an integer and a pointer.

Then I continue reading the assembly and find two interesting calls:

```asm
call strcpy
```

and later another:

```asm
call strcpy
```

Then I continue reading the assembly and find the first call to `strcpy`.

To understand what is copied, I follow the registers.

First:

    mov 0xc(%ebp),%eax

loads `argv` into `%eax`.

Then:

    add $0x4,%eax
    mov (%eax),%eax

moves to `argv[1]` and dereferences it.

Now:

    eax = argv[1]

The value is saved:

    mov %eax,%edx

so:

    edx = argv[1]

Next the program loads the first structure:

    mov 0x1c(%esp),%eax

Earlier, this location was used to store the pointer returned by the first `malloc(8)`.

Therefore:

    eax = s1

Then:

    mov 0x4(%eax),%eax

reads the field at offset 4.

So:

    eax = s1->buf

Current state:

    eax = s1->buf
    edx = argv[1]

The compiler is now preparing the arguments for `strcpy`.

    mov %edx,0x4(%esp)
    mov %eax,(%esp)

Stack before the call:

    esp+0 -> s1->buf
    esp+4 -> argv[1]

Finally:

    call strcpy

which is equivalent to:

    strcpy(s1->buf, argv[1]);

A few instructions later, exactly the same sequence appears again.

The only difference is that this time the program loads:

    argv[2]

and

    s2->buf

before calling `strcpy`.

Therefore the second call becomes:

    strcpy(s2->buf, argv[2]);

At this point I notice something important:

    buf1 size = 8 bytes
    buf2 size = 8 bytes

but `strcpy()` performs no size checking.

This means a long `argv[1]` can overflow `buf1` and corrupt adjacent heap data.

